e fate of one minority group of Greek citizens during the war and explores various aspects of its relations with the conquerors, the conquered, and concerned bystanders. His book contains new archival material and interviews with survivors. It supersedes much of the general literature on the subject of Greek Jewry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)zGreece. 0aJewszGreecexHistoryy20th century. 0aSephardimzGreecexHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804772495zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804772495423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804772495.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles